subSubSection.paragraph:
Diagnosis.
Body form in lateral view strongly dorsoventrally convex, appearing humped in scutellar region; elytral glabrous region of male (
Figs. 2C
, 
7A
) cordiform, along suture extending ca. 7/9 length of elytra, laterally expanded in anterior 2/3 to considerably wider than pronotal glabrous region, posterior 1/3 strongly acuminate with rounded margins; female elytral glabrous region (
Figs. 3C
, 
7E
) dissimilar to male, ‘nycteriform’ (batwing-shaped); elytral apex of both sexes similar, evenly rounded without apicolateral sinuation, epipleural angle indistinct; male protibia (
Fig. 4C
) wedge-shaped, protibial apex truncate with weakly prominent distolateral angle; male protarsus (
Fig. 4C
) over 1/2 length of protibia, protarsomeres 1–4 mostly similar in width; mesoventrite without medial pit; aedeagus (
Fig. 7B–D
) with median lobe weakly tapered, apex weakly constricted in lateral view (
Fig. 7C
); female reproductive tract (
Fig. 7G
) with additional sclerite between gonocoxae (
Fig. 7F
), fertilization duct as in 
Fig. 7H
.

Male genitalia. Aedeagus (
Fig. 7B
) with median lobe ca. 5/6 length of parameres, weakly tapered, apical 1/6 of aedeagus acuminate with straight lateral margins, apex weakly constricted in lateral view (
Fig. 7C
), operculum as in (
Fig. 7D
); parameres narrowly rounded apically (
Fig. 7B
).

Female genitalia. Reproductive tract with large sac-like spermatheca (
Fig. 7G
); fertilization duct sclerotized, highly convoluted (
Fig. 7H
); small sclerite present posterior to oviduct; additional round sclerite present between gonocoxae; gonocoxae narrow, apically rounded, lateral margins weakly sinuate (
Fig. 7F
).
